h1. User Persona and Story

Meet Yuki, a project manager in a bustling software development company. She's responsible for keeping track of her team's work hours, tasks, project progress, and budget management. With multiple projects running simultaneously and various financial responsibilities, it's not an easy task. That's when Yuki discovers Freeekout.

Freeekout (the app that we make) is a comprehensive time tracking and project management app that integrates seamlessly with Slack, FREEE, and Atlassian, making it easy for Yuki to monitor her team's work hours, progress, and budgets on all her projects. With real-time data synced across platforms, Yuki never misses a beat.

As Yuki's team members work, they use Freeekout to track their time, assign it to the proper project codes (cost centers), and log labor costs. The app also integrates with their Jira, ensuring accurate time logs for all project-related activities. This streamlined process keeps manual time entry in one place and minimizes errors.

Note：FREEE has some features, but they are clunky, take many clicks, and require a lot of manual entry [https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000345.000006428.html|https://prtimes.jp/main/html/rd/p/000000345.000006428.html|smart-link] 

Freeekout will have premium features that simplify the RFP process, helping Yuki create, manage, and track RFPs with ease. 

*_What is an RFP?_*

{quote}_A_ +_request for proposal_+ _is a document that offers a proposal by an agency or company interested in buying a service, or an asset, to potential clients for business proposals._{quote}

The app’s premium tier offers tools for budget estimation, allowing Yuki to estimate project cost ranges, and submit well-informed budget requests. With its powerful budget tracking and projection features, Yuki can monitor expenses in real-time and make adjustments as needed to keep projects on track financially.

When it's time for Yuki to generate reports, Freeekout's reporting and analytics features come to the rescue. Yuki can quickly create customized reports, analyze her team's performance, and make data-driven decisions. Plus, Freeekout's platinum version allows her to dive even deeper into the data, providing insights that help optimize her team's workflow, productivity, and financial management.

In no time, Freeekout becomes an indispensable tool for Yuki and her team. Project management, time tracking, and budgeting are no longer a hassle, and Yuki can focus on what matters most - delivering successful projects on time and within budget.

With Freeekout, streamline your time tracking, project management, and budgeting processes. Get started for free today and unlock the full potential of your team with our premium features.



h1. What do we know?

# We do not want to manually input our time tracking into multiple tools each day/week/month.
# We do not want people to have to manually manage these things each day/wee/month/year.
# +We ourselves+ want do want a way to clearly show what our “money in” and “money out” situation is on the macro and micro levels.
## We need more data sources “in” to FREEE.
## We need an aggregator if there are multiple sources.
# +Potential partners and investors+ clearly show what our “money in” and “money out” situation is on the macro and micro levels.
# We know we have a problem with time estimation for incoming workloads.
## We know we could use a prediction model.
### We know we have data historical data in FREEE and Jira - however it may be limited.
### We know we could sell an anonymized copy of the model.
# We know we have a problem with time tracking for existing workloads.
## For example, inputting “time spent” into FREEE and Jira.
## Not having the ability to cross reference time spent in places like GitHub or Salesforce (where dev/biz can spend a lot of time).
# We know we cannot combine different team’s costs into a single source of truth - to understand the total “money out” for a project/product.
## Biz Teams
## Dev Teams
## Corporate/HR
## Marketing
## Tooling
## Infra costs
## and so on

h1. What do we not know?

# 
# What is the market cap for this kind of product?
## In Japan
## Overseas
# What features can we offer for free, that don’t cost us too much money?
# What would users pay?
## For bronze/silver/gold/platinum type tiers?
#

fields.description:
{panel:bgColor=#deebff}
this is a work in progress, it could and should change often, as we learn about the Jira, freee APIs
{panel}

Example flow for first time set up of Jira > spreadsheet for calculating total costs of labor towards a project each month:

# Jira filter is created to show all epics in the organization
## example [freekin epics filter]
# The admin panel asks you to input that filter ID, so it has a list of epics to recommend
## In our examples case, it is *10053 (*[*link*|https://datafluct-international.atlassian.net/issues/?filter=10053]*)*
# If the epic title has brackets with the client name, examples: [becoz] [yamaga], when the regular expression is set to
{noformat} [yamaga]|[becoz]{noformat}
then the app recognizes that it belongs to the freee project ID of DS210068 (as shown in [this spreadsheet|https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1TBfexpbeSYKYRLLyCbgUO2k9XeYzADuJi-iSDDjyKpI/edit#gid=1857566999]) 
# In the admin panel, users will see options to ask users about. Guiding them to make the correct connection between an Epic and project cost code.
## In the first version, this can be more manual, as there is a limited number of use cases.
## But in later versions, this could be automated, or highly recommended so it is very simple for users to set up. 
# In the first version, the output will be printed to a spreadsheet that [~accountid:6353a81401c2ff842c175b58] shares
## In later versions, it will directly input to freee, but at first we just need to pull info from Jira with their API.

fields.description:
Researching to get data from Jira Automation with json format because the default response data is not good for manipulating in backend.

Using these links for references:

[https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-articles/Automation-for-Jira-Send-web-request-using-Jira-REST-API/ba-p/1443828|https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-articles/Automation-for-Jira-Send-web-request-using-Jira-REST-API/ba-p/1443828|smart-link] 

[https://support.atlassian.com/cloud-automation/docs/issue-data-automation-format-payload-for-send-web-request/|https://support.atlassian.com/cloud-automation/docs/issue-data-automation-format-payload-for-send-web-request/|smart-link] 

[https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-discussions/Jira-Automation-Rules-Send-Web-Request-and-APIs-protected-by/td-p/1568456|https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-discussions/Jira-Automation-Rules-Send-Web-Request-and-APIs-protected-by/td-p/1568456|smart-link] 

[https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-questions/JSON-body-from-Automation-web-request-is-in-wrong-format/qaq-p/1940227|https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-questions/JSON-body-from-Automation-web-request-is-in-wrong-format/qaq-p/1940227|smart-link] 

[https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-Software-questions/Automation-How-retrieve-data-in-quot-Send-web-request-quot/qaq-p/2153217|https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Jira-Software-questions/Automation-How-retrieve-data-in-quot-Send-web-request-quot/qaq-p/2153217|smart-link]

Data fetched from data has correct json format to be convenient for store it later.
